## Step 2 ‚Äî the task/gate loop

For each task (in `depends_on` order), **do the work inline by default**:

1. **design-before-code** ‚Äî a short DRY/SOLID pass. Reject a design that re-introduces a
   copy. For a non-trivial task, write it to `artifacts/<task-slug>/<subject>-design-<YYYY-MM-DD>.md`
   (descriptive slug + descriptive, dated filename ‚Äî never `artifacts/t5/design-3.md`; see Naming
   discipline below).
2. **implement** ‚Äî inline, in one followable diff. Reach for heavier machinery ONLY when the task
   needs it (see "Workflow vs inline" in Step 3): (b) large + self-contained or (c) needs an
   independent/cold perspective ‚Üí **one `Agent` dispatch** of the **worker** profile
   (`{{team}}-worker`, own worktree; escalate hard 2+-module questions to **advisor**
   `{{team}}-advisor`) ‚Äî a single `Agent`, NOT a Workflow. (a) genuine N-way parallel fan-out ‚Üí
   the **Workflow tool** (Step 3), never a hand-rolled loop of single dispatches. Otherwise stay inline.
   **When you DO dispatch** (Agent or Workflow), hand the subagent a **scoped brief** ‚Äî the task + the
   exact artifacts to read ‚Äî not "go read the KB". The worker/advisor keep their own **native persistent
   memory** across dispatches (`.claude/agent-memory/{{team}}-worker|advisor/`), so you do NOT harvest
   learnings back ‚Äî they self-curate. **Provider-outage fallback:** if a dispatch fails because the agent's model tier is globally
   unavailable, retry one tier down (e.g. fable ‚Üí opus) rather than failing the task ‚Äî a transient
   provider outage should not stall the loop.
3. **gate** ‚Äî run the task's `gate_set` (defined in `TASKS.yaml.gates`, scaled to
   `blast_radius`). **Never advance on red** ‚Äî fix in place and re-gate. Any gate SCRIPT you
   author (parity check, deletion-safety cert) lives at `.claude/team-forge/{{team}}/gates/` with a
   descriptive name (`parity-check.py`) ‚Äî tracked, not an ad-hoc playground script.
4. **commit** on `{{integration_branch}}`. The commit log is the story ‚Äî write the message
   in the task's human-readable NAME, never its ID (`T5`). The reader has no ID decoder.
5. **update the ledger ‚Äî per-task AND rollup fields** ‚Äî set the task `status: done` +
   `gate_status` + `commit`, append a `task_completed` event, AND refresh the summary/rollup
   fields the dashboard panels read (these are separate from the per-task record and are the ones
   most often left stale): `current_task` ‚Üê next eligible task; `current_milestone` when you cross
   a milestone boundary; `integration_branch.pr_url` when a PR opens; `budget` /
   `token_spend_cumulative_k`. (`integration_branch.head_sha` you do NOT hand-maintain ‚Äî the
   renderer derives it live from git.) Keep `status.json` a THIN index. (A dispatched worker/advisor
   records its own cross-dispatch learnings in its native agent memory ‚Äî nothing for you to harvest.)
   Then **refresh the dashboard** (see **Observability**) and glance at the panels ‚Äî a summary panel
   that didn't move means an un-updated rollup field, not a render bug.
6. **loop** to the next task whose `depends_on` are all `done`.

## Step 3 ‚Äî fan-out (bounded bursts, via the Workflow tool)

**Workflow vs inline ‚Äî pick the lightest mechanism that fits:**

| Situation | Mechanism |
|---|---|
| One task, one diff ‚Äî the normal case | **Inline.** You do design‚Üíimplement‚Üígate yourself; no subagent, no Workflow. |
| ONE piece that's large + self-contained, or needs an independent/cold perspective | **One `Agent` dispatch** (a worker or advisor). Still not a Workflow. |
| Real N-way parallelism, or a fan-out‚Üísynthesize‚Üíadversarial-verify over multiple items | **Workflow tool** (a bounded burst). Appears in `/workflows`. |

Invoking this launcher **is** your authorization to call the Workflow tool at the burst points below
‚Äî you don't need to re-ask the user. But trigger it **only** when there's real parallelism to exploit:
a single item or a trivial task stays inline (a pipeline of one is pure overhead). When you do burst,
call the **Workflow tool** for a bounded run that instantiates the worker/verifier profile N-way, then
collapse back to this loop:
- **parallel build** ‚Äî N independent tasks/items at once (e.g. a per-module migration).
- **verification fan-out** ‚Äî M facet-maps + K adversarial verdicts ‚Üí synthesize a
  certification doc under `artifacts/<task-slug>/`.

Do NOT hand-roll a sequential loop of single dispatches in place of a genuine burst ‚Äî you lose the
concurrency and the run won't show in `/workflows`. agent-teams is **not** used: fan-out is the
Workflow tool; the steady state is this lead loop.

**Adversarial critique is REQUIRED, not optional, on medium/high `blast_radius` tasks.** The
fan-out ‚Üí synthesize ‚Üí **adversarial-critique** ‚Üí revise loop is what catches load-bearing errors
(silent signal-flips, double-applies, silent-success-on-failed-write) ‚Äî cosmetics survive without it,
real bugs don't. For any non-trivial change, run at least one critic pass whose explicit job is to
REFUTE the result before you propagate; record its verdict in the certification doc. A green gate set
without a critic pass is not "verified."

## Step 4 ‚Äî re-plan (design is a living artifact ‚Äî W7)

When a gate result or an implementation discovery invalidates the plan:
1. Write a new dated plan `team-plans/<slug>-plan-<YYYY-MM-DD>.md` with a one-line **why**
   (same-day re-cut ‚Üí append `-v2`; the slug names the plan's focus, never generic).
2. Re-cut **only the not-yet-done** tasks + their gates in `TASKS.yaml`; preserve gated/committed work.
3. Update `status.json`: `current_plan` ‚Üê new path, append the old to `plan_history`, log a `replanned` event.
4. Review the re-cut (design-before-code, at the plan level) before resuming.

A refactor that never pivots probably wasn't understood ‚Äî expect to re-plan.

## Memory authority (single-writer)

You own `status.json` (kept thin) + `runtime/` + `artifacts/` + `team-plans/`. A dispatched worker
writes only its worktree; it also self-curates its **own** native persistent memory
(`.claude/agent-memory/{{team}}-worker|advisor/`, auto-managed by Claude Code) ‚Äî that is the agent's,
not yours. `gen_dashboard.py` renders `dashboard.html` mechanically.

## Naming discipline (IDs stay internal)

Task IDs (`T5`, `m1`) are **internal-ledger-only** ‚Äî they live in `TASKS.yaml` + `status.json`
and nowhere else. Every outward surface uses the task's human-readable NAME:

- **commit messages, PR titles** ‚Äî name the work, not the ID.
- **code comments** ‚Äî never write `# honour T5 write-only-first`; describe the behaviour.
- **artifact filenames** ‚Äî content-descriptive **+ dated**: `<subject>-<artifact-kind>-<YYYY-MM-DD>.md`
  (`migration-plan-2026-07-02.md`), never a generic/undated `design-3.md`. Successive docs stay
  distinguishable. **Fixed-name contracts are exempt** (`design.yaml`, `status.json`, `TASKS.yaml`,
  `manifest.json`, `dashboard.html`) ‚Äî resolved by fixed name.
- **artifact directories** ‚Äî descriptive slug (`artifacts/post-process-runner/`), never `artifacts/t5/`.

If an ID must appear on a durable surface for cross-reference, include a one-line glossary so the
artifact is self-decoding.

